and picnic utensils.

31:54.151 --> 31:56.417
- PAUL: Fascinating.
- MARY: Mm-hmm.

31:56.417 --> 31:57.814
EUBANKS: If we ever take
separate vacations,

31:57.814 --> 31:59.288
I am sending my wife to blank...

31:59.288 --> 32:01.994
- Oh. Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

32:01.994 --> 32:04.062
(chatter continues over TV)

32:06.462 --> 32:09.694
So, how are the boys?

32:09.694 --> 32:12.400
Broken in body and spirit.

32:13.799 --> 32:17.273
Okay, well, it is the holidays,
so, you know, go easy on them.

32:17.273 --> 32:18.769
Oh, please.

32:18.769 --> 32:21.145
They've had it easy
their whole lives.

32:21.145 --> 32:22.938
You don't know that.

32:22.938 --> 32:24.478
Did you?

32:25.976 --> 32:28.548
Besides, everybody should be
with their people on Christmas.

32:28.548 --> 32:30.286
- WOMAN: Hawaii, probably.
- EUBANKS: Hawaii. All right.

32:30.286 --> 32:31.551
He says he's gonna send you
to Santa Ana

32:31.551 --> 32:33.487
and he's going to Las Vegas.

32:33.487 --> 32:35.027
MAN: Nobody can watch you
in Siberia.

32:35.027 --> 32:36.721
Where are you going?

32:36.721 --> 32:38.888
- To Vegas.
- Las Vegas?

32:38.888 --> 32:41.561
- Yeah.
- (sighs)

32:41.561 --> 32:43.563
- No.
- (audience murmurs, laughs)

32:43.563 --> 32:45.895
Those two are going to get
a divorce.

32:45.895 --> 32:47.534
How do you know?

32:47.534 --> 32:49.668
I recognize that look
of stale disappointment.

32:49.668 --> 32:51.670
- (chuckling)
- She hates him.

32:51.670 --> 32:53.738
Oh.

32:53.738 --> 32:55.806
How long were you married?

32:55.806 --> 32:57.742
I was engaged
to Curtis's father.

32:57.742 --> 33:00.910
- Mm.
- But he died
before I gave birth.

33:00.910 --> 33:02.714
Harold.

33:02.714 --> 33:05.255
He worked in the shipyard.

33:05.255 --> 33:07.752
And one day, they was
carrying this big, uh,

33:07.752 --> 33:11.162
cargo pallet,
and the cable snapped.

33:11.162 --> 33:13.065
Hit him right across the head.

33:15.531 --> 33:17.234
They were good men.

33:17.234 --> 33:18.730
Both of them.

33:18.730 --> 33:22.030
And neither of them
made it to 25.

33:22.030 --> 33:24.604
My baby wasn't even 20.

33:25.937 --> 33:28.212
I'm so sorry.

33:28.212 --> 33:31.215
I took this job
when Curtis was small

33:31.215 --> 33:32.942
because I wanted to ensure

33:32.942 --> 33:35.010
that he was going to have
a good education.

33:35.010 --> 33:37.551
- You know he flourished here.
- Yes. No, he was a great kid.

33:37.551 --> 33:38.948
- I had him one semester.
- Mm-hmm.

33:38.948 --> 33:40.587
Very insightful.

33:40.587 --> 33:42.655
Mm-hmm. He hated you.

33:44.131 --> 33:46.329
He said you were a real asshole.

33:47.398 --> 33:50.399
Well, uh, like I said...
(chuckles)

33:50.399 --> 33:52.500
sharp kid. Insightful.

33:55.769 --> 33:58.737
He had his heart set
on Swarthmore.

33:58.737 --> 34:01.575
And he had the grades,
but I didn't have the money.

34:01.575 --> 34:04.644
Even with financial aid,
it wasn't enough.

34:04.644 --> 34:08.879
So, when he got called up
and no student deferment,

34:08.879 --> 34:10.749
off he went.

34:11.818 --> 34:13.752
Do you know what he said to me?

34:13.752 --> 34:17.723
He said,
"Hey, Ma, look at the upside.

34:17.723 --> 34:22.464
When I get discharged, I can go
to college on the GI Bill."

34:24.534 --> 34:26.435
College.

34:32.542 --> 34:34.608
And here we are.

34:37.448 --> 34:39.481
With my Curtis
in the cold ground

34:39.481 --> 34:42.011
and those boys
safe and warm in their beds.

34:44.015 --> 34:45.520
It's like you said.

34:45.520 --> 34:47.115
How'd you say it?

34:47.115 --> 34:49.084
"Life is like
a henhouse ladder."

34:49.084 --> 34:50.921
- (Paul chuckles)
- That's right.

34:50.921 --> 34:53.198
I can hear everything
you're saying from the kitchen.

34:53.198 --> 34:55.123
Especially that Kountze kid.

34:55.123 --> 34:57.664
Crown prince of all
the little assholes.

34:57.664 --> 34:59.336
- (chuckles)
- MAN (over TV): It's zero.

34:59.336 --> 35:00.832
EUBANKS:
Zero. She said it is zero!

35:00.832 --> 35:02.636
Couple number one,
Mike and Sherry McCray,

35:02.636 --> 35:04.704
you are our grand prize winner!

35:04.704 --> 35:07.377
(applause, cheering over TV)

35:13.748 --> 35:16.386
All right, you fetid layabouts.

35:16.386 --> 35:18.113
It's daylight in the swamp!

35:18.113 --> 35:19.620
(clanging)

35:19.620 --> 35:21.017
Arise!

35:21.017 --> 35:22.821
(students groaning)

35:22.821 --> 35:25.659
("Carol of the Drum
(Little Drummer Boy)" playing)

35:25.659 --> 35:27.364
Speed, gentlemen.

35:27.364 --> 35:29.465
Speed!

35:29.465 --> 35:33.161
Without sufficient exercise,
the body devours itself.

35:33.161 --> 35:34.701
That's it!

35:34.701 --> 35:36.571
Good.

35:37.706 --> 35:39.475
(coughing)

35:39.475 --> 35:41.345
♪ Our finest gifts we bring,
pa-rum pum pum pum ♪

35:41.345 --> 35:43.215
(sniffs, coughs)

35:44.449 --> 35:47.384
♪ To lay before the King,
pa-rum pum pum pum ♪

35:47.384 --> 35:51.586
♪ Rum pum pum pum,
rum pum pum pum ♪

35:51.586 --> 35:56.525
♪ So to honor him,
pa-rum pum pum pum ♪

35:56.525 --> 36:00.232
♪ When we come ♪

36:02.599 --> 36:04.929
♪ Baby Jesus... ♪

36:04.929 --> 36:06.733
What about your car?

36:06.733 --> 36:08.867
We can take it, go somewhere.
Boston, maybe?

36:08.867 --> 36:10.902
Nah, we'd get in
so much trouble.

36:10.902 --> 36:13.245
Face it. We're stuck.

36:13.245 --> 36:15.445
If we just had some way
to get out of here.

36:15.445 --> 36:18.008
- Yo.
- Just split.

36:18.008 --> 36:20.516
Well, you could put a chopper
down right in the quad.

36:20.516 --> 36:21.682
What?

36:21.682 --> 36:23.552
A helicopter, dumbass.

36:23.552 --> 36:25.686
His old man's the CEO
of Pratt & Whitney.

36:25.686 --> 36:27.292
Yeah, he's got his own bird.

36:27.292 --> 36:29.019
He takes it from Stamford
to the city every morning.

36:29.019 --> 36:30.394
Lands it right in the backyard.

36:30.394 --> 36:32.121
The pilot's name is Wild Bill.

36:32.121 --> 36:35.223
- Wild Bill?
- Yeah.

36:35.223 --> 36:37.368
He flew up to Haystack with it.

36:37.368 --> 36:40.030
Took the presents
and everything, minus me.

36:40.030 --> 36:42.637
Flying with presents,
like Santa Claus.

36:42.637 --> 36:44.067
Yeah.

36:44.067 --> 36:45.937
Just like Santa Claus.
(whistles)

36:45.937 --> 36:47.807
Hey.

36:47.807 --> 36:49.743
Oh, let's go, let's go!

36:49.743 --> 36:53.450
You know, if I were back home
right now in Provo,

36:53.450 --> 36:56.816
it'd be really warm inside.

36:56.816 --> 37:00.622
And my mom, she'd be making me
baked apples,

37:00.622 --> 37:04.219
and the whole house would smell
like cinnamon and brown sugar.

37:04.219 --> 37:06.122
That sounds so nice.

37:07.499 --> 37:08.927
JASON:
Touchdown!

37:08.927 --> 37:11.226
(Teddy grunting)

37:11.226 --> 37:12.667
Hey!

37:12.667 --> 37:14.097
(laughs) That's what you get

37:14.097 --> 37:15.967
for ratting me out,
you little Mormon!

37:15.967 --> 37:18.673
- (grunts, laughs)
- ALEX: What?

37:18.673 --> 37:19.905
TEDDY:
Let's go!

37:19.905 --> 37:21.841
What's Fork Union?

37:21.841 --> 37:26.274
Uh, before, you said you don't
want to end up at Fork Union.

37:26.274 --> 37:29.684
It's a military academy
in Virginia.

37:29.684 --> 37:32.489
That's where I'm going if I get
kicked out of school again.

37:32.489 --> 37:35.690
How many schools
have you been kicked out of?

37:35.690 --> 37:37.362
Three.

37:37.362 --> 37:39.188
That's why I'm still a junior.

37:39.188 --> 37:41.465
- Give or take a semester.
- ALEX: It's gone!

37:42.501 --> 37:44.028
My glove's gone.

37:44.028 --> 37:47.031
Twisted fucker orphaned
that glove on purpose.

37:47.031 --> 37:50.408
Left you with one so the loss
would sting that much more.

37:54.744 --> 37:57.206
♪ ♪

38:12.597 --> 38:14.894
♪ ♪

38:14.894 --> 38:17.226
(deep, shuddering breath)

38:32.111 --> 38:34.177
♪ ♪

38:48.292 --> 38:50.765
(crying)

38:59.974 --> 39:01.237
Hey.

39:02.449 --> 39:04.779
You all right?

39:04.779 --> 39:06.715
(voice shaking):
I had a nightmare.

39:06.715 --> 39:08.849
I get nightmares too.

39:08.849 --> 39:11.280
I'm always falling or drowning.

39:11.280 --> 39:13.282
Also...

39:13.282 --> 39:15.284
(sobbing)

39:15.284 --> 39:17.154
I had an accident.

39:23.327 --> 39:25.195
Yeah, you did.

39:25.195 --> 39:27.967
Shh. Stop crying.

39:27.967 --> 39:30.574
If they hear you,
they'll crucify you.

39:30.574 --> 39:33.302
Which would be ironic
since you're Buddhist.

39:33.302 --> 39:35.909
I know this is
an excellent school,

39:35.909 --> 39:38.406
and my brothers went here,

39:38.406 --> 39:40.881
but I miss my family,

39:40.881 --> 39:43.114
and I have no friends.

39:44.150 --> 39:47.349
Yeah, well,
friends are overrated.

39:48.825 --> 39:51.496
I'll help you hide the sheets
in the morning, all right?

39:51.496 --> 39:55.291
In the meantime, find a dry spot
and try to get some sleep.

39:55.291 --> 39:57.128
Thank you.

40:02.542 --> 40:04.443
Fucking asparagus.

40:27.633 --> 40:29.666
(clearing throat)

40:31.736 --> 40:33.461
(whispering):
Are you kidding me?

40:33.461 --> 40:36.299
It's only 11:00,
and he's already lit.

40:36.299 --> 40:38.136
I can smell the whiskey on him.

40:38.136 --> 40:40.776
Can you blame him?
It's freezing in here.

40:40.776 --> 40:43.273
It's fucking Greenland in here.

40:43.273 --> 40:46.012
(helicopter whirring
in distance)

40:59.060 --> 41:00.664
What the hell is that?

41:00.664 --> 41:02.732
(whirring continues)

41:25.790 --> 41:27.086
JASON:
I knew it!

41:27.086 --> 41:29.561
He finally caved,
the big softie.

41:30.861 --> 41:33.598
Hey, any of you guys
like to ski?

41:35.030 --> 41:37.063
♪ ♪

41:38.704 --> 41:40.363
PAUL:
Thank you.

41:40.363 --> 41:42.332
Goodbye, now.

41:42.332 --> 41:45.038
(chatter continues indistinctly)

41:45.038 --> 41:47.106
♪ ♪

41:48.945 --> 41:50.582
Yes!

41:57.085 --> 41:58.788
Well, good news, gentlemen.

41:58.788 --> 42:01.384
I was able to reach Dr. Woodrup
and your parents.

42:01.384 --> 42:03.826
Uh, most of them, anyway.

42:04.961 --> 42:07.423
Try calling again.
Just one more time, please.

42:07.423 --> 42:09.029
There's no point.

42:09.029 --> 42:10.734
The front desk says
they're not answering.

42:10.734 --> 42:12.901
He says they're away
on some excursion.

42:12.901 --> 42:14.969
- Excursion.
- (chuckles)

42:14.969 --> 42:17.609
I'm as disappointed as you are,
if not more so.

42:17.609 --> 42:19.644
I could have been spending
the rest of my vacation

42:19.644 --> 42:21.811
reading mystery novels.

42:21.811 --> 42:24.473
Maybe they're back now.
Just call again, please.

42:25.685 --> 42:27.146
Okay.

42:32.857 --> 42:34.450
Happy holidays.

42:34.450 --> 42:36.518
Same to you.

42:39.160 --> 42:41.160
Take care, Tully.

42:42.592 --> 42:44.900
I guess that just
leaves you, huh?

42:44.900 --> 42:47.133
Be sure to do all your homework.

42:48.675 --> 42:50.301
Oh, almost forgot.

42:50.301 --> 42:52.468
I found that picture
you were looking for.

42:53.636 --> 42:55.680
Merry Christmas, Mr. Tully.

42:58.443 --> 43:00.377
(Teddy laughing)

43:02.722 --> 43:04.381
Bye, Angus.

43:08.288 --> 43:11.256
♪ ♪

43:11.256 --> 43:13.324
(indistinct chatter)

43:34.479 --> 43:37.788
(Paul sighs)

43:37.788 --> 43:40.582
Well, let's make the best
of it, shall we?

43:42.355 --> 43:44.322
(sighs)

43:44.322 --> 43:46.830
WOMAN (over TV):
Oh, I suppose, um,

43:46.830 --> 43:48.799
- Stan Laurel, maybe, because...
- EUBANKS: Stan Laurel.

43:48.799 --> 43:50.867
All right. Your husband said
his favorite silent movie star

43:50.867 --> 43:53.705
is Rudolph Valentino.

43:53.705 --> 43:56.169
- Oh. He is good.
- MAN: Well, yeah.

43:56.169 --> 43:57.401
(laughter over TV)

43:57.401 --> 43:59.073
(Paul chuckles)

43:59.073 --> 44:00.668
EUBANKS: The last of our
five-point questions, girls...

44:00.668 --> 44:03.011
How about you?
You ever been married?

44:03.011 --> 44:06.311
(scoffs, chuckles)

44:06.311 --> 44:08.720
No. I did get close once.

44:08.720 --> 44:10.854
Right after college.

44:10.854 --> 44:12.482
MARY:
And?

44:12.482 --> 44:14.484
PAUL:
We came to our senses.

44:14.484 --> 44:19.159
This is not exactly a face
forged for romance, Mary.

44:19.159 --> 44:21.865
Yeah, and the...

44:21.865 --> 44:23.658
And, you know...

44:23.658 --> 44:24.901
What?

44:25.970 --> 44:27.772
Nothing.

44:27.772 --> 44:30.775
I don't know.
I like being alone.

44:30.775 --> 44:34.273
I've always found myself drawn
to the aesthetic.

44:34.273 --> 44:36.176
Like a monk.

44:36.176 --> 44:38.442
The forgoing
of sensual pleasures

44:38.442 --> 44:40.378
for the achievement
of spiritual goals.

44:40.378 --> 44:41.885
- Spiritual goals?
- Mm-hmm.

44:41.885 --> 44:43.447
- You?
- (chuckles)

44:43.447 --> 44:44.888
What spiritual goals
are we talking about?

44:44.888 --> 44:46.252
You go to church?

44:46.252 --> 44:48.254
- Mm, only when required.
- Exactly.

44:48.254 --> 44:50.553
When's the last time
you even left campus?

44:50.553 --> 44:52.555
- I go into town all the time.
- Oh.

44:52.555 --> 44:54.557
For groceries
and various errands

44:54.557 --> 44:56.064
- and appointments.
- Mm-hmm.

44:56.064 --> 44:58.363
(sighs, stammers)

44:58.363 --> 45:01.234
Okay, yes,
I don't leave campus often.

45:01.234 --> 45:02.730
I don't really feel the need.

45:02.730 --> 45:04.468
Let me ask you something.

45:04.468 --> 45:07.911
If you could go anywhere
on Earth, where would you go?

45:07.911 --> 45:09.440
(chuckling):
Oh.

45:09.440 --> 45:11.783
Greece, Italy,

45:11.783 --> 45:14.786
Egypt, Peru, Carthage.

45:14.786 --> 45:16.887
Tunisia now, of course.

45:16.887 --> 45:19.450
In college, I started
a monograph on Carthage.

45:19.450 --> 45:22.288
I'd like to finish that someday.

45:22.288 --> 45:25.929
(sighs) A monograph is
like a book, o-only shorter.

45:25.929 --> 45:28.096
I know what a monograph is.

45:28.096 --> 45:30.164
Why not just write a book?

45:31.871 --> 45:34.531
I'm not sure I have
an entire book in me.

45:36.106 --> 45:39.206
You can't even dream
a whole dream, can you?

45:41.441 --> 45:43.980
(grunting softly)

45:47.645 --> 45:49.546
(groans)

46:00.900 --> 46:02.361
(sighs)

46:02.361 --> 46:04.836
Monet, Manet, Picasso.

46:04.836 --> 46:06.838
(passes gas)

46:10.338 --> 46:13.009
(takes deep breath)

46:16.916 --> 46:18.982
(Paul snoring)

46:33.493 --> 46:36.527
("Crying, Laughing, Loving,
Lying" by Labi Siffre playing)

46:41.402 --> 46:43.941
♪ Crying ♪

46:46.011 --> 46:50.772
♪ Crying never did nobody
no good no how ♪

46:55.086 --> 46:57.218
♪ That's why I ♪

47:00.058 --> 47:03.521
♪ I don't cry ♪

47:08.132 --> 47:10.935
♪ Laughing ♪

47:12.697 --> 47:17.436
♪ Laughing sometimes does
somebody some good somehow ♪

47:19.440 --> 47:21.946
♪ That's why I ♪

47:23.983 --> 47:27.644
♪ I'm laughing now ♪

47:29.054 --> 47:31.549
♪ That's why I ♪

47:33.388 --> 47:37.258
♪ I'm laughing now. ♪

47:50.141 --> 47:52.174
(song ends)

48:14.297 --> 48:16.891
(takes deep breath)

48:16.891 --> 48:18.365
<i>(Paul clears throat)</i>

48:19.368 --> 48:21.137
I have a surprise.

48:23.108 --> 48:25.735
Uh, these were a gift to me,

48:25.735 --> 48:28.804
and I would like to share them
with both of you.

48:29.873 --> 48:32.445
Look at them.
Look at all the festive shapes.

48:32.445 --> 48:35.679
Snowflakes and gingerbread men.
A tree.

48:35.679 --> 48:38.286
A little mitten. (chuckles)

48:38.286 --> 48:40.552
Mmm. (chuckles)

48:41.984 --> 48:43.456
Mmm.

48:44.492 --> 48:46.525
May I go to the bathroom, sir?

48:46.525 --> 48:48.362
You may.

48:51.829 --> 48:53.433
(sighs)

48:53.433 --> 48:55.303
Well, I'm trying.

48:55.303 --> 48:57.371
(laughing)

48:59.969 --> 49:01.375
Mmm.

49:01.375 --> 49:02.970
If you don't have a single room,

49:02.970 --> 49:04.840
uh, I'll take a junior suite
or the equivalent.

49:04.840 --> 49:06.809
I fully understand
it's the holidays,

49:06.809 --> 49:08.448
but it's kind of an emergency.

49:08.448 --> 49:10.318
Mm-hmm. Yeah, sure.

49:10.318 --> 49:11.814
Mr. Tully, what are you doing?

49:11.814 --> 49:13.222
Uh, no, no credit card.

49:13.222 --> 49:14.619
I'll pay cash
or traveler's checks.

49:14.619 --> 49:15.950
I didn't say
you could use the phone.

49:15.950 --> 49:17.457
(chuckling):
Okay, I see.

49:17.457 --> 49:18.458
Is there anywhere else
you could recommend?

49:18.458 --> 49:20.031
Maybe downtown or...

49:20.031 --> 49:22.132
- Was that a hotel?
- None of your business.

49:22.132 --> 49:25.135
It is absolutely my business.
I'm looking after you.

49:25.135 --> 49:26.994
Looking after me? Really?

49:26.994 --> 49:29.073
- Like what? Like my warden?
- (scoffs)

49:29.073 --> 49:30.635
Like my butler?

49:30.635 --> 49:32.505
There's nobody here, okay?

49:32.505 --> 49:34.408
Just us two losers
and a grieving mom.

49:34.408 --> 49:36.146
So let's cut the shit.

49:36.146 --> 49:38.148
You stay out of my way,
and I'll stay out of yours.

49:38.148 --> 49:40.007
- That's a detention.
- (groans)

49:40.007 --> 49:41.712
You just earned yourself
a detention, sir.

49:41.712 --> 49:43.516
Now, get back here!

49:43.516 --> 49:46.420
Being here with you is already
one big fucking detention!

49:46.420 --> 49:48.983
Son of a bitch,
that's another detention!

49:48.983 --> 49:50.754
("Deck the Halls" by
The Swingle Singers playing)

49:50.754 --> 49:52.030
Mr. Tully!

49:53.957 --> 49:56.331
I don't know what you're
playing at, Mr. Tully,

49:56.331 --> 49:58.828
but you are courting disaster!

49:58.828 --> 50:01.402
Without exercise,
the body devours itself.

50:01.402 --> 50:04.207
You are careening
towards suspension!

50:04.207 --> 50:05.703
(grumbles)

50:09.115 --> 50:11.148
(panting)

50:16.155 --> 50:18.221
(panting heavily)

50:30.994 --> 50:33.236
Don't even think about it,
Mr. Tully.

50:33.236 --> 50:37.372
You are a hair's breadth
from suspension.

50:37.372 --> 50:40.243
I'll wash my hands of you,
you hear me?

50:40.243 --> 50:42.245
Wash my hands.

50:45.107 --> 50:46.810
Stop right there.

50:46.810 --> 50:50.011
You know the gym is
strictly off-limits.

50:51.421 --> 50:53.388
